The 2001 profitability assessment was based on the assumption that both the border and the Bohemian High Mountains are simultaneously under traffic.
At the time of the examination it was obvious that the section through the Bohemian High Mountains would not be opened at the original date.
This reduces the aforementioned EIRR values.
The cost of both sections at 31.12.2005 was €897 million excluding VAT, which is 27.4% higher than the 2001 profitability assessment.
In addition, there is a risk that Section 0805 will be given another more elaborate route, which would affect the profitability of the project.
The profitability assessment showed that the construction of both sections of the motorway is economically justified with a daily traffic volume of at least 18 000 cars per day in 2010. The forecast for 2008 predicted 22 940 cars per day.
However, a study on diversion routes as an alternative to the missing section through the Bohemian Mountains assumes a traffic volume of between 12 600 and 13 750 cars per day in 2007. The project will then be below the profitability limit.
Higher traffic on the routes intended to replace the missing section with the Bohemian High Mountains is likely to result in traffic jams and thus increased external costs, which were not taken into account in the original economic assessment.
The abovementioned reduction in revenue and increase in costs means that the already low EIRR for the construction of the borderline section of the D 8 will not be achieved.
The construction of the borderline section of the D 8 is therefore uneconomical.
The construction of the A 17 also resulted in cost increases, as in the construction of the two above-mentioned sections of D 8.
As part of the overall economic assessment for the 1992 Federal Transport Plan, the Federal Ministry responsible for Transport assumed investment costs of around €320 million.
Thus, it determined a benefit/cost ratio of 4.6.
In the meantime, costs have increased to approximately €670 million and the use/cost ratio has decreased by more than half.
Regardless of the parallel tests with the NKÚ in the years 2003 to 2005, the BRH had tested the cost-effectiveness of the design and construction of the A17 motorway.
In doing so, he found that the authority responsible for the authorisation required an unnecessary landscape tunnel for the third section of the A 17.
During the examination, the BRH succeeded in convincing the Federal Ministry and the Road Construction Administration of the superfluous landscape tunnel.
This avoided €10 million in construction costs and €150 000 in annual operating costs.
When examining the first section of the A 17, the BRH found that the construction measure was insufficiently prepared.
The following example makes this vivid:
During the planning phase, the road construction administration did not require the condition of the rock at the surface of the Dölzschener Wand, as it was difficult to access.
It was only when the tunnel propulsion reached the wall that it did.
It showed that the rock was more weathered than was assumed in the tender.
Complex measures such as anchorages, injections and stone chip protection nets for around €3.3 million were required.
The Road Construction Administration paid not only the costs of additional services, which are already required, such as securing the Dölzschener Wand, but also for those that would not have been required if the construction was properly prepared.
This includes expenses due to impaired construction processes (€3.2 million), additional training of the advance team (€0.5 million) and increased wages and material prices due to the extension of construction time (€7 million).
This additional expenditure of around €10.7 million is not offset by any lasting added value.
The Federal Republic of Germany took these and other measures as an occasion to call on the Federal Ministry to better exercise the specialist supervision for major road construction measures which it is responsible for.
In this context, it should be urging for road construction administrations to introduce quality assurance systems.
Advantages of cooperation for BRH and NKÚ The cooperation met the expectations of both auditors.
The BRH received insights on the planning, procurement and implementation of the construction of the border bridge.
Both auditors developed a database of bridge and tunnel prices that will be helpful in future audits.
The NKÚ noted that the main structural parameters for bridges, tunnels and roadway of the D 8 do not differ from those of the A 17.
The auditors of both auditors involved in the cooperation gained valuable experience which will be useful in future audits.
